ODIQ exists to catalyse open data for the benefit of everyone
Our Vision:
ODIQ will be an effective, self-sustaining organisation that is valued and trusted by its stakeholders across government, industry, academia and research and the community.  It will strengthen the global ODI network, leveraging the network to create value in Australia.  
ODIQ will be acknowledged as a centre of excellence in building relationships and capability to derive economic and social value from open data.  It will enable tangible outcomes in areas important to the community, including health, education, transport, the environment and public safety.  It will provide an effective independent broker for business, government, research and entrepreneurs to collaborate and solve problems using open data.
ODIQ will contribute to the creation of a professional, sustainable open data community with the capacity, knowledge and tools needed to create genuine value from open data.  Leveraging open data and emergent technologies will position Australia as an advanced digitally-savvy economy driven through entrepreneurship and innovation.  ODIQ will be instrumental in harnessing the contributions of research, academia, training organisations, industry, non-profits and members of the community to this end.
ODIQ will be a place where people are imaginative, innovative, collaborative and committed.  It will be vibrant, inclusive and fun to be part of.

Our product provides an automated and streamlines way to obtain key development and land use-planning information on a property level.  Our SaaS platform helps real estate developers and planners simplify the archaic process of pulling a variety of regulatory and planning information together from government sources. results.org_additional: This is getting a bit more suetbcjive, but I much prefer the Zune Marketplace. The interface is colorful, has more flair, and some cool features like  Mixview' that let you quickly see related albums, songs, or other users related to what you're listening to. Clicking on one of those will center on that item, and another set of  neighbors  will come into view, allowing you to navigate around exploring by similar artists, songs, or users. Speaking of users, the Zune  Social  is also great fun, letting you find others with shared tastes and becoming friends with them. You then can listen to a playlist created based on an amalgamation of what all your friends are listening to, which is also enjoyable. Those concerned with privacy will be relieved to know you can prevent the public from seeing your personal listening habits if you so choose.

It would be significantly helpful if amendments and bills were broken down categorically into what their chief cause or effect will be. For example, we use data from GovTrack.us to analyze each candidate's legislative record, however, we must first analyze the legislation to categorize what its intended impact is.

Additionally, more data at the local level would be supremely helpful. The more local we go, the less data that is available. More information on money in local politics, as well as legislative records, would allow us to better inform voters in local elections, where voter turnout is suffering most.
